a whole. The volume begins with an introduction to how mountains are defined, followed by a comprehensive treatment of their physical geography: origins, climatology, snow and ice, landforms and geomorphic processes, soils, vegetation, and wildlife. The concluding chapters provide an introduction to the human geography of mountains: attitudes toward mountains, people living in mountain regions and their livelihoods and interactions within dynamic environments, the diverse types of mountain agriculture, and the challenges of sustainable mountain development.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aGeomorphology. 0aHuman geography. 0aMountain people. 0aMountains. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Geography.2bisacsh  aanthropology.  acomprehensive resource.  aconservation.  acritical resources.  adynamic environments.  aearth science.  aearth sciences.  aecology.  aenvironmental.  ageographical processes.  ageography.  ageology.  ageomorphic processes.  agives readers.  aglobal importance.  aglobal population.  ahuman geography.  alandforms.  amountain agriculture.  amountain ranges.  amountains.  anature.  aphysical geography.  ascience.  asustainale mountain development.  awater resources.  awilderness.1 aBach, Andrew J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernbaum, Edwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirkeland, Karl W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByers, Alton C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByers, Alton C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCunha, Stephen F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDexter, Leland R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab